The writer of the article applauds the House of Representatives for passing the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act (VAWA) with bipartisan support. They urge the Senate to follow suit and renew and strengthen this important law. The article highlights the significance of VAWA in transforming the country's response to violence against women and mentions the bipartisan efforts to expand its provisions for better protection and prevention. The writer emphasizes the ongoing need for progress, as many women, particularly women of color, Native American women, and LGBTQ individuals, continue to face domestic violence, dating violence, sexual assault, and stalking. They also mention that the COVID-19 pandemic has worsened the threat of intimate partner violence. The writer stresses that this issue transcends political affiliations and calls on the Senate to come together in a strong bipartisan coalition to pass VAWA.